Regression¶

Simulation¶

Assumptions in Linear Regression:¶

  • Linearity $ Y = \beta X$
  • Independence $cov(Y_i, Y_j)=0, i \ne j$
  • Homoskedasticity (Constant Variance) $var(Y_i)=\sigma^2 $
  • Normality $Y_i \sim N(\beta_0 + \beta_1 X_{i1} + \beta_2 X_{i2} + .. + \beta_p X_{ip}, \sigma^2)$

Reference: Module 1-1 annotated version.

Summary Linear Fit for first simulation¶

The following summary of linear fit shows

  • intercept is 1.032 i.e. 1.032 average unit of $y_i$ for a sample with $x_i = 0$.
  • intercept with p-value < 0.05, we reject null hypothesis.
  • $\beta_1 = 2.06565$ with p-value < 0.05, we reject null hypothesis i.e. $\beta_1 = 0$ is not false.
  • R-squared = 0.9728 suggests high explainable variance.

Summary Diagnostics Plot¶

The following summary of linear fit shows

Linearity:¶

  • The fitted vs observed values plot seems to fit well, linearity is preserved, as expected.

Normality¶

  • The Residuals vs theoretical quantiles plot seems to suggest there is no normality violation.
  • Bell curve was included however is not suitable for analysing normality, but was referred from textbook (section 6.1.2 on Normality). ("Histograms and boxplots are not suitable for checking normality")
  • Additionally conducting the Shapiro-Wilk normality test, it seems that null hypothesis that residuals are normal is rejected since p-value is large (> alpha = 0.05). Thus data came from a normally distributed population holds true.

Constant Variance¶

  • The fitted vs residuals plot suggests constant variance, with no specific pattern indicating non-constant variance.
  • Between fitted values -0.25 to 0.25, there is some variance. Around either ends of the curve, the variance seems constant.

(a) outliers, (b) leverage points, and (b) potentially influential points¶

Correlation between errors:¶

The plot for correlation between errors suggests negative and positive correlation. This is emphasized by the summary of fit for successive pairs of errors, where p-value large suggests errors are uncorrelated i.e we fail to reject null hypothesis. Intercept is not included, since residuals have zero mean.

Homoscadesticity, Outliers:¶

  • Squareroot of Standardized residuals vs fitted values: if the red line is approximately horizontal, then homoscadesticity is met. But the line is curved in this case, suggests homoscadesticity is not met. The rows 106, 140 and 180 have highest standardized residuals. Generally highest residuals may indicate outliers. This suggests an observation whose dependent variable value is unusual given predictor variable value. finding the Studentized residuals for the model suggests 1 values with highest residuals. Second plot shows outliers and box plot for each of predictor variables as well as response variable. values >6 and < -4 for y and values > 2.5 and < -2.5 are listed as an outlier.

Displaying using true outliers from studentized residuals shows the outliers in the dataset. finally excluding the outlier rows (where y > 0.4), significantly changes the coefficients and residuals. This shows that there are multiple outliers in the data.

Leverage:¶

An observation with extreme predictor value is a point with high leverage. Leverage is a measure of how far an independent value deviates from its mean. High leverage points can have greater impact on estimate of regression coefficients. from the leverage points (from hatvalues function), sorted values suggest there is no evidence that if any observations have high leverage. the leverage value on y-axis for each index plotted on x-axis suggests leverage statsitic trend.

Influential observations:¶

An observation is said to be influential if removing it significantly changes the estimates of regression coefficients. It is a product of leverage and outlierness. Influential point may or may not be an outlier. Cooks distance finds distances for np points by removing each of the points and calculating product of residual effect and the leverage. With Half normal plot over cooks distance suggests the influential points.

Here the 6 possible influential points are 22, 116,141,153 and 155. By removing the max of cook's distance value from data and finding linear fit, suggests change in x coefficient by ~25% and change in y. This change seems sensitive.

dfbeta plot suggests change in coeffiecient with and without each of observation. Dfbetas plot shows the change in each of coefficient when an observed value i is removed w.r.t full model with i. Most of changes do seems sensitive. 88, 143 and 189 are the influential rows in dataset.

Added variable plots:¶

Added variable plots suggest that what is the influence of removing 100, 165 and 180 impact the each of coefficient i.e. how blue line in each variable plot is impacted. Blue line is regression coefficient for the predictor variable.
